text: I would have to say getting a job at GMO straight out of college, I got a call from GMO, from their HR person for an interview. And I literally had to Google what they did. Now, keep in mind that I don't come from a business background. My mom's an artist. My dad's a doctor. I went to college, was originally a poli sci or government major. I got into economics simply because I liked the quantitative angle as a way of explaining social sciences. And then I graduated into the teeth of the financial crisis. So of course, bubbles and crises were interesting to me. But I had never really heard of a lot of these investment firms. So it was just through sheer luck, and my resume got passed around and somehow ended up on the desk of the COO over there at the time. And then I got my first internship, which then turned into a full-time offer. And I think that set me on a very interesting path the rest of my career. I didn't know what I was doing, but I was doing a lot of research. value investing was. I never read security analysis. I showed up at GMO and at Chancellor, one of my mentors gave me security analysis and told me to read it. And I actually sat there and spent all that time reading about railroads and private utilities and all these sorts of things. And it was kind of an eye-opening experience for me since I had basically no experience in finance or even accounting or investing. So that set me on an interesting track. And then, of course, the value angle and quantitative investing, these are all things I would never have even dreamed about being my career for the next 10 plus years. But here we are.
